Providing these examples left us with subconscious suggestions for which word cloud should go with each color palette. The questions were self-explanatory enough, so I think you would have gotten better results had you left out the examples.

column342: Many of my answers may have been influenced by the presence of one or two words in the word cloud. For instance, colors that I would associate with a few of the larger words would not go with one or two of the smaller words. Additionally, I felt that some of the colors that I associated with more "feminine" traits (pastels with housekeeping, gardening, etc.) were answers that I didn't want to provide because I felt that it conflicted my own belief that this answer would perpetuate some kind of sexism and stereotyping. Additionally, I noticed on one group that I decided not to associate on color palette with a word cloud because the word cloud seemed to be geared toward nature and the colors omitted any green.

column342: I don't like your your word-clouds: every cloud that mentions 'man' has 'business' as the first- or second-most prominent word, and then either 'sport' or 'hygiene' as another of the most prominent words.  The problem is not that the conception of masculinity you're examining is narrow, it's that it's so constrained, that these words are taken as so closely correlated in your cloeds, that I don't know exactly what you'll be able to extrapolate from any of these particular clouds that will help you to separate conclusions about masculinity from conclusions about, say, professionality or private industry or business acumen.  You seem to have painted yourself into a bit of a corner.  The clouds that mention 'woman' don't seem to have quite this problem, though of course they all seem to mention either 'fashion' or 'sex' -- these words just aren't nearly so prominent.
